1
00:00:00,100 --> 00:00:14,637
'For while all things were in quiet silence and the night was in the midst of her course, etc.' Here in time we make holiday because the eternal birth which God the Father bore and bears unceasingly in eternity is now born in time, in human nature.

2
00:00:14,587 --> 00:00:18,050
St Augustine says this birth is always happening.

3
00:00:18,050 --> 00:00:21,275
But if it happen not in me what does it profit me?

4
00:00:21,275 --> 00:00:24,050
What matters is that it shall happen in me.

5
00:00:24,050 --> 00:00:33,562
We intend therefore to speak of this birth as taking place in us; as being consummated in the virtuous soul; for it is in the perfect soul that God speaks his Word.

6
00:00:33,562 --> 00:00:45,225
What I shall say is true only of the perfected man, of him who has walked and is still walking in the way of God; not of the natural undisciplined man who is entirely remote from and unconscious of this birth.

7
00:00:45,225 --> 00:00:54,237
There is a saying of the wise man: 'When all things lay in the midst of silence then leapt there down into me from on high, from the royal throne, a secret word.

8
00:00:54,237 --> 00:00:56,625
This sermon is about this word.

9
00:00:56,625 --> 00:00:59,662
Concerning it three things are to be noted.

10
00:00:59,662 --> 00:01:07,600
The first is, where-abouts in the soul God the Father speaks his Word, where she is receptive of this act, where this birth befalls.

11
00:01:07,600 --> 00:01:12,637
It is bound to be in the purest, loftiest, subtlest part of the soul.

12
00:01:12,637 --> 00:01:25,437
Verily, an God the Father in his omnipotence had endowed the soul with a still nobler nature, had she received from him anything yet more exalted, then must the Father have delayed this birth for the presence of this greater excellence.

13
00:01:25,437 --> 00:01:40,462
The soul in which this birth shall come to pass must be absolutely pure and must live in gentle fashion, quite peaceful and wholly introverted: not running out through the five senses into the manifoldness of creatures, but altogether within and harmonised in her summit.

14
00:01:40,462 --> 00:01:42,062
That is its place.

15
00:01:42,062 --> 00:01:45,050
Anything inferior is disdained by it.

16
00:01:45,050 --> 00:02:12,412
The second part of this discourse has to do with man's conduct in relation to this act, this interior speaking, this birth: whether it is more profitable to co-operate in it—perhaps by creating in the mind an imaginary image and disciplining oneself thereon by reflecting that God is wise, omnipotent, eternal, or whatever else one is able to excogitate about God—so that the birth may come to pass in us through our own exertion and merit; or whether it is more profitable and conducive to this

17
00:02:12,412 --> 00:02:24,362
birth from the Father to shun all thoughts, words and deeds as well as all mental images and empty oneself, maintaining a wholly God-receptive attitude, such that one’s own self is idle letting God work.

18
00:02:24,362 --> 00:02:27,387
Which conduct subserves this birth best?

19
00:02:27,387 --> 00:02:32,337
The third point is the profit and how great it is, which accrues from this birth.

20
00:02:32,337 --> 00:02:47,250
Note in the first place that in what I am about to say I intend to avail myself of natural proofs that ye yourselves can grasp, for though I put more faith in the scriptures than myself, nevertheless it is easier and better for you to learn by means of arguments that can be verified.

21
00:02:47,250 --> 00:02:52,850
First we will take the words: “In the midst of the silence there was spoken in me a secret word.

22
00:02:52,850 --> 00:02:57,850
But, Sir, where is the silence and where the place in which the word is spoken?

23
00:02:57,964 --> 00:03:05,676
As I said just now, it is in the purest part of the soul, in the noblest, in her ground, aye in the very essence of the soul.

24
00:03:05,626 --> 00:03:17,626
That is mid-silence, for thereinto no creature did ever get, nor any image, nor has the soul there either activity or understanding; therefore she is not aware of any image either of herself or any creature.

25
00:03:17,626 --> 00:03:21,114
Whatever the soul effects she effects with her powers.

26
00:03:21,114 --> 00:03:24,814
When she understands she understands with her intellect.

27
00:03:24,814 --> 00:03:27,639
When she remembers she does so with her memory.

28
00:03:27,639 --> 00:03:30,189
When she loves she does so with her will.

29
00:03:30,189 --> 00:03:33,739
She works then with her powers and not with her essence.

30
00:03:33,739 --> 00:03:37,239
Now every exterior act is linked with some means.

31
00:03:37,239 --> 00:03:44,451
The power of seeing is brought into play only through the eyes; elsewhere she can neither do nor bestow such a thing as seeing.

32
00:03:44,451 --> 00:03:50,464
And so with all the other senses: their operations are always effected through some means or other.

33
00:03:50,464 --> 00:03:59,901
But there is no activity in the essence of the soul; the faculties she works with emanate from the ground of the essence, but in her actual ground there is mid-stillness.

34
00:03:59,901 --> 00:04:10,976
Here alone is rest and a habitation for this birth, this act, wherein God the Father speaks his Word, for it is intrinsically receptive of naught save the divine essence, without means.

35
00:04:10,976 --> 00:04:15,089
Here God enters the soul with his all, not merely with a part.

36
00:04:15,089 --> 00:04:17,526
God enters the ground of the soul.

37
00:04:17,526 --> 00:04:20,701
None can touch the ground of the soul but God only.

38
00:04:20,701 --> 00:04:25,889
No creature is admitted into her ground; it must stop outside in her powers.

39
00:04:25,889 --> 00:04:30,201
There it sees the image whereby it has been drawn in and found shelter.

40
00:04:30,201 --> 00:04:36,676
For when the soul-powers contact a creature they set to to make of the creature an image and likeness which they absorb.

41
00:04:36,676 --> 00:04:38,689
By it they know the creature.

42
00:04:38,689 --> 00:04:46,689
Creatures cannot go into the soul, nor can the soul know anything about a creature which she has not willingly taken the image of into herself.

43
00:04:46,689 --> 00:04:53,251
She approaches creatures through their present images: an image being a thing that the soul creates with her powers.

44
00:04:53,251 --> 00:05:03,426
Be it a stone, a rose, a man, or anything else that she wants to know about, she gets out the image of it which she has already taken in and is thus enabled to unite herself with it.

45
00:05:03,426 --> 00:05:08,851
But an image received in this way must of necessity enter from without through the senses.

46
00:05:08,851 --> 00:05:12,976
Consequently there is nothing so unknown to the soul as herself.

47
00:05:12,976 --> 00:05:18,289
The soul, says a philosopher, can neither create nor absorb an image of herself.

48
00:05:18,289 --> 00:05:20,989
So she has nothing to know herself by.

49
00:05:20,989 --> 00:05:25,901
Images all enter through the senses, hence she can have no image of herself.

50
00:05:25,901 --> 00:05:28,576
She knows other things but not herself.

51
00:05:28,576 --> 00:05:33,351
Of nothing does she know so little as of herself, owing to this arrangement.

52
00:05:33,351 --> 00:05:41,739
Now thou must know that inwardly the soul is free from means and images, that is why God can freely unite with her without form or similitude.

53
00:05:41,739 --> 00:05:47,826
Thou canst not but attribute to God without measure whatever power thou dost attribute to a master.

54
00:05:47,826 --> 00:05:53,951
The wiser and more powerful the master the more immediately is his work effected and the simpler it is.

55
00:05:53,951 --> 00:06:01,764
Man requires many instruments for his external works; much preparation is needed ere he can bring them forth as he has imagined them.

56
00:06:01,764 --> 00:06:11,689
The sun and moon whose work is to give light, in their mastership perform this very swiftly: the instant their radiance is poured forth, all the ends of the world are full of light.

57
00:06:11,689 --> 00:06:17,114
More exalted are the angels, who need less means for their works and have fewer images.

58
00:06:17,114 --> 00:06:20,064
The highest Seraph has but a single image.

59
00:06:20,064 --> 00:06:24,626
He seizes as a unity all that his inferiors regard as manifold.

60
00:06:24,626 --> 00:06:36,214
Now God needs no image and has no image: without image, likeness or means does God work in the soul, aye, in her ground whereinto no image did ever get but only himself with his own essence.

61
00:06:36,214 --> 00:06:38,214
This no creature can do.

62
00:06:38,214 --> 00:06:44,351
How does God the Father give birth to his Son in the soul: like creatures, in image and likeness?

63
00:06:44,351 --> 00:06:46,164
No, by my faith!

64
00:06:46,164 --> 00:06:50,039
but just as he gives him birth in eternity and no otherwise.

65
00:06:50,039 --> 00:06:52,776
Well, but how does he give him birth there?

66
00:06:52,948 --> 00:06:53,848
See.

67
00:06:53,798 --> 00:07:02,273
God the Father has perfect insight into himself, profound and thorough knowledge of himself by means of himself, not by means of any image.

68
00:07:02,273 --> 00:07:07,635
And thus God the Father gives birth to his Son, in the very oneness of the divine nature.

69
00:07:07,635 --> 00:07:16,073
Mark, thus it is and in no other way that God the Father gives birth to his Son in the ground and essence of the soul and thus he unites himselfwith her.

70
00:07:16,073 --> 00:07:21,960
Were any image present there would not be real union and in real union lies thy whole beatitude.

71
00:07:21,960 --> 00:07:27,023
Now haply thou wilt say: ‘But there is nothing innate in the soul save images.

72
00:07:27,023 --> 00:07:28,610
No, not so!

73
00:07:28,610 --> 00:07:41,910
If that were true the soul would never be happy, for God cannot make any creature wherein thou canst enjoy perfect happiness, else were God not the highest happiness and final goal, whereas it is his will and nature to be the alpha and omega of all.

74
00:07:41,910 --> 00:07:44,185
No creature can be happiness.

75
00:07:44,185 --> 00:07:52,248
And here indeed can just as little be perfection, for perfection (perfect virtue that is to say) results from perfection of life.

76
00:07:52,248 --> 00:08:01,210
Therefore verily thou must sojourn and dwell in thy essence, in thy ground, and there God shall mix thee with his simple essence without the medium of any image.

77
00:08:01,210 --> 00:08:06,973
No image represents and signifies itself: it stands for that of which it is the image.

78
00:08:06,973 --> 00:08:15,085
Now seeing that thou hast no image save of what is outside thee, therefore it is impossible for thee to be beatified by any image whatsoever.

79
00:08:15,244 --> 00:08:33,756
The second point is, what it does behove a man to do in order to deserve and procure this birth to come to pass and be consummated in him: is it better for him to do his part towards it, to imagine and think about God, or should he keep still in peace and quiet so that God can speak and act in him while he merely waits on God’s operation?

80
00:08:33,756 --> 00:08:50,281
At the same time I repeat that this speaking, this act, is only for the good and perfect, those who have so absorbed and assimilated the essence of virtue that it emanates from them naturally, without their seeking; and above all there must live in them the worthy life and lofty teaching of our Lord Jesus Christ.

81
00:08:50,281 --> 00:08:57,831
Such are permitted to know that the very best and utmost of attainment in this life is to remain still and let God act and speak in thee.

82
00:08:57,831 --> 00:09:03,906
When the powers have all been withdrawn from their bodily forms and functions, then this Word is spoken.

83
00:09:03,906 --> 00:09:08,744
Thus he says: ‘in the midst of the silence the secret word was spoken to me.

84
00:09:08,744 --> 00:09:21,931
The more completely thou art able to in-draw thy faculties and forget those things and their images which thou has taken in, the more, that is to say, thou forgettest the creature, the nearer thou art to this and the more susceptible thou art to it.

85
00:09:21,931 --> 00:09:35,019
If only thou couldst suddenly be altogether unaware of things, aye, couldst thou but pass into oblivion of thine own existence as St Paul did when he said: ‘Whether in the body I know not, or out of the body I know not, God knoweth!

86
00:09:35,019 --> 00:09:54,706
Here the spirit had so entirely absorbed the faculties that it had forgotten the body: memory no longer functioned, nor understanding, nor the senses, nor even those powers whose duty it is to govern and grace the body; vital warmth and energy were arrested so that the body failed not throughout the three days during which he neither ate nor drank.

87
00:09:54,706 --> 00:10:02,894
Even so fared Moses when he fasted forty days on the mount and was none the worse for it: on the last day he was as strong as on the first.

88
00:10:02,894 --> 00:10:10,119
Thus a man must abscond from his senses, invert his faculties and lapse into oblivion of things and of himself.

89
00:10:10,119 --> 00:10:16,769
Anent which a philosopher apostrophised the soul: ‘Withdraw from the restlessness of external activities!

90
00:10:16,769 --> 00:10:24,394
And again: ‘Flee away and hide thee from the turmoil of outward occupations and inward thoughts for they create nothing but discord!

91
00:10:24,394 --> 00:10:33,381
If God is to speak his Word in the soul she must be at rest and at peace; then he speaks in the soul his Word and himself: not an image but himself.

92
00:10:33,381 --> 00:10:40,669
Dionysius says: ‘God has no image nor likeness of himself seeing that he is intrinsically all good, truth and being.

93
00:10:40,669 --> 00:10:46,181
God performs all his works, in himself and outside himself, simultaneously.

94
00:10:46,181 --> 00:10:54,019
Do not fondly imagine that God, when he created the heavens and the earth and all creatures, made one thing one day and another the next.

95
00:10:54,019 --> 00:11:03,369
Moses describes it thus it is true, nevertheless he knew better: he did so merely on account of those who are incapable of understanding or conceiving otherwise.

96
00:11:03,369 --> 00:11:06,481
All God did was: he willed and they were.

97
00:11:06,481 --> 00:11:09,731
God works without instrument and without image.

98
00:11:09,731 --> 00:11:18,931
And the freer thou art from images the more receptive thou art to his interior operation; and the more introverted and oblivious thou art the nigher thou art thereto.

99
00:11:18,931 --> 00:11:36,319
Dionysius exhorted his disciple Timothy in this sense saying: ‘Dear son Timothy, do thou with untroubled mind swing thyself up above thyself and above thy powers, above all modes and all existences, into the secret, still darkness, that thou mayest attain to the knowledge of the unknown super-divine God.

100
00:11:36,319 --> 00:11:38,619
All things must be forsaken.

101
00:11:38,619 --> 00:11:41,231
God scorns to work among images.

102
00:11:41,356 --> 00:11:47,193
Now haply thou wilt say: ‘What is it that God does without images in the ground and essence?

103
00:11:47,143 --> 00:11:58,668
That I am incapable of knowing, for my soul-powers can receive only in images; they have to recognise and lay hold of each thing in its appropriate image: they cannot recognise a bird in the image of a man.

104
00:11:58,668 --> 00:12:05,493
Now since images all enter from without, this is concealed from my soul, which is most salutary for her.

105
00:12:05,493 --> 00:12:12,656
Not-knowing makes her wonder and leads her to eager pursuit, for she knows clearly that it is but knows not how nor what it is.

106
00:12:12,656 --> 00:12:19,268
No sooner does a man know the reason of a thing than immediately he tires of it and goes casting about for something new.

107
00:12:19,268 --> 00:12:22,843
Always clamouring to know, he is ever inconstant.

108
00:12:22,843 --> 00:12:27,431
The soul is constant only to this unknowing knowing which keeps her pursuing.

109
00:12:27,431 --> 00:12:34,993
The wise man said concerning this: ‘In the middle of the night when all things were in quiet silence there was spoken to me a hidden word.

110
00:12:34,993 --> 00:12:37,581
It came like a thief, by stealth.

111
00:12:37,581 --> 00:12:40,306
What does he mean by a word that was hidden?

112
00:12:40,306 --> 00:12:43,468
The nature of a word is to reveal what is hidden.

113
00:12:43,468 --> 00:12:48,868
It appeared before me, shining out withintent to reveal and giving me knowledge of God.

114
00:12:48,868 --> 00:12:50,793
Hence it is called a word.

115
00:12:50,793 --> 00:12:53,318
But what it was remained hidden from me.

116
00:12:53,318 --> 00:12:57,693
That was its stealthy coming ‘in a whispering stillness to reveal itself.

117
00:12:57,693 --> 00:13:02,143
It is just because it is hidden that one is and must be always after it.

118
00:13:02,143 --> 00:13:06,531
It appears and disappears: we are meant to yearn and sigh for it.

119
00:13:06,531 --> 00:13:12,131
St Paul says we ought to pursue this until we espy it and not stop until we grasp it.

120
00:13:12,131 --> 00:13:25,131
When he returned after having been caught up into the third heaven where God was made known to him and where he beheld all things, he had forgotten nothing, but it was so deep down in his ground that his intellect could not reach it: it was veiled from him.

121
00:13:25,131 --> 00:13:30,856
He was therefore obliged to pursue it and search for it in himself, not outside himself.

122
00:13:30,856 --> 00:13:34,706
It is not outside, it is inside: wholly within.

123
00:13:34,706 --> 00:13:41,956
And being convinced of this he said, ‘I am sure that neither death nor any affliction can separate me from what I find within me.

124
00:13:41,956 --> 00:13:53,606
There is a fine saying of one heathen philosopher to another about this, he says: ‘I am aware of something in me which sparkles in my intelligence: I clearly perceive that it is somewhat but what I cannot grasp.

125
00:13:53,606 --> 00:13:57,443
Yet methinks if I could only seize it I should know all truth.

126
00:13:57,443 --> 00:14:01,306
To which the other philosopher replied: ‘Follow it boldly!

127
00:14:01,306 --> 00:14:06,731
for if thou canst seize it thou wilt possess the sum-total of all good and have eternal life!

128
00:14:06,731 --> 00:14:19,706
St Augustine expresses himself in the same sense: ‘I am conscious of something within me that plays before my soul and is as a light dancing in front of it: were this brought to steadiness and perfection in me it would surely be eternal life!

129
00:14:19,706 --> 00:14:21,631
It hides yet it shows.

130
00:14:21,631 --> 00:14:27,768
It comes, but after the manner of a thief, with intent to take and to steal all things from the soul.

131
00:14:27,768 --> 00:14:35,456
By emerging and showing itself somewhat it purposes to decoy the soul and draw it towards itself to rob it and take itself from it.

132
00:14:35,456 --> 00:14:40,631
As saith the prophet: ‘Lord take from them their spirit and give them instead thy spirit.

133
00:14:40,631 --> 00:14:48,931
This too the loving soul meant when she said: ‘My soul dissolved and melted away when Love spoke his word: when he entered I could not but fail.

134
00:14:48,931 --> 00:15:02,443
And Christ signified it by his words: ‘Whosoever shall leave aught for my sake shall be repaid an hundredfold, and whosoever will possess me must deny himself and all things and whosoever will serve me must follow me nor go any more after his own.

135
00:15:02,443 --> 00:15:08,606
Now peradventure thou wilt say: ‘But, Sir, you are wanting to change the natural course of the soul!

136
00:15:08,606 --> 00:15:12,581
It is her nature to take in through the senses, in images.

137
00:15:12,581 --> 00:15:14,906
Would you upset this arrangement?

138
00:15:15,076 --> 00:15:15,851
No!

139
00:15:15,801 --> 00:15:23,513
But how knowest thou what nobility God has bestowed on human nature, what perfections yet uncatalogued, aye yet undiscovered?

140
00:15:23,513 --> 00:15:33,626
Those who have written of the soul’s nobility have gone no further than their natural intelligence could carry them: they never entered her ground, so that much remained obscure and unknown to them.

141
00:15:33,626 --> 00:15:38,738
I will sit in silence and hearken to what God speaketh within me,’ said the prophet.

142
00:15:38,738 --> 00:15:42,938
Into this retirement steals the Word in the darkness of the night.

143
00:15:42,938 --> 00:15:53,501
St John says, ‘The light shines in the darkness: it came unto its own and as many as received it became in authority sons of God: to them was given power to become God’s sons.

144
00:15:53,501 --> 00:15:58,151
Mark now the fruit and use of this mysterious Word and of this darkness.

145
00:15:58,151 --> 00:16:08,426
In this gloom which is his own the heavenly Father’s Son is not born alone: thou too art born there a child of the same heavenly Father and no other, and to thee also he gives power.

146
00:16:08,426 --> 00:16:10,526
Observe how great the use.

147
00:16:10,526 --> 00:16:21,676
No truth learned by any master by his own intellect and understanding, or ever to be learned this side the day of judgment, has ever been interpreted at all according to this knowledge, in this ground.

148
00:16:21,676 --> 00:16:33,413
Call it an thou wilt an ignorance, an unknowing, yet there is in it more than in all knowing and understanding without it, for this outward ignorance lures and attracts thee from all understood things and from thyself.

149
00:16:33,413 --> 00:16:42,588
This is what Christ meant when he said: ‘Whosoever denieth not himself and leaveth not father and mother and is not estranged from all these, he is not worthy of me.

150
00:16:42,588 --> 00:16:49,751
As though to say: he who abandons not creaturely externals can neither be conceived nor born in this divine birth.

151
00:16:49,751 --> 00:16:55,426
But divesting thyself of thyself and of everything external thereto does indeed give it thee.

152
00:16:55,426 --> 00:17:03,601
And in very truth I believe, nay I am sure, that the man who is established herein can in no wise be at any time separated from God.

153
00:17:03,601 --> 00:17:07,088
I hold he can in no wise lapse into mortal sin.

154
00:17:07,088 --> 00:17:13,951
He would rather suffer the most shameful death, as the saints have done before him, than commit the least of mortal sins.

155
00:17:13,951 --> 00:17:21,351
I hold that he cannot willingly commit, nor yet consent to, even a venial sin, whether in himself or in another.

156
00:17:21,351 --> 00:17:32,001
So strongly is he drawn and attracted to this way, so much is he habituated to it, that he could never turn to any other: to this way are directed all his senses, all his powers.

157
00:17:32,001 --> 00:17:40,338
May the God who has been born again as man assist us in this birth, continually helping us, weak man, to be born again in him as God.

158
00:17:40,338 --> 00:17:41,288
Amen.
